🛠️ DML — Data Manipulation Language

Used to manage and manipulate the actual data within tables.

  • Commands: INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, MERGE
  • Effect: Adds, modifies, or removes rows from tables.
  • Transactional: DML operations can be rolled back or committed.

Core DML Commands

  • INSERT: Adds new records into a table.
  • UPDATE: Modifies existing records based on given conditions.
  • DELETE: Removes specific records from a table.
  • MERGE: Combines insert, update, and delete logic in a single operation.

💡 Note: DML changes data content — always use WHERE clauses to avoid accidental bulk updates.

🛠️ DML — Data Manipulation Language

INSERT

Adds new records into a table.

  • Simple Insert: Inserting a single row of data.
  • Row Constructor Insert: Inserting multiple rows of data.

💡 Note: If a column is not in column_list, the Database Engine must be able to provide a value based on the definition of the column; otherwise, the row cannot be loaded. The Database Engine automatically provides a value for the column if the column:.

  • Has an IDENTITY property. The next incremental identity value is used.
  • Has a default. The default value for the column is used.
  • Has a timestamp data type. The current timestamp value is used.
  • Is nullable. A null value is used.
  • Is a computed column. The calculated value is used.

💡 Tip: Use column_list For Inserting data that is not in the same order as the table columns

INSERT Based on SELECT

The INSERT ... SELECT statement allows inserting data into a table using results from another table or query.

  • Purpose: Efficiently copy or transform data from one table into another.
  • Use Case: Data migration or creating summary tables.
  • Key Rule: The number and data types of columns in SELECT must match the target table’s column list.

Example:

INSERT INTO EmployeeArchive (EmployeeID, FullName, HireDate)
SELECT EmployeeID, FullName, HireDate
FROM Employees
WHERE IsActive = 0;

💡 Tip: Always specify column names in both INSERT and SELECT to avoid errors if the table structure changes.

🗄️ Temporary Tables in SQL Server

Tables you create temporarily to store data for a short time while running your queries.

  • ⏳ Scope: Exists only for the duration of the session or connection.
  • 📍 Location: Stored in tempdb system database.
  • 🛠️ Use Cases:
    • To break a big query into easier steps
    • To store intermediate results
    • Improve performance in large transactions
  • Behavior: Automatically removed when session ends.

Types of Temporary Tables

  • 📘 Local Temporary Tables (#Temp):
    • Visible only to the current window/session.
    • Dropped automatically when your session/window closes.
  • 🌍 Global Temporary Tables (##Temp):
    • Accessible to all sessions.
    • Deleted when the last referencing session ends.

Example:

            -- Local temporary table
            CREATE TABLE #Employees (Id INT, Name NVARCHAR(100));
            
            -- Insert into temp
            INSERT INTO #Employees VALUES (1, 'John');
            
            -- Query temp table
            SELECT * FROM #Employees;
            
            -- Global temporary table
            CREATE TABLE ##Logs (LogId INT, Message VARCHAR(200));

🛠️ DML — Data Manipulation Language

UPDATE

Modifies existing records in a table.

  • Simple Update: Updating one or more columns for specific rows.
  • Conditional Update: Applying changes only to rows matching a condition (using WHERE).
  • Update Based on Another Table: Updating rows using data from a different table.

Example:

                    -- Update a single column
                    UPDATE Employees 
                    SET Salary = 5000 
                    WHERE EmployeeID = 1;
                    
                    -- Update multiple columns
                    UPDATE Employees
                    SET Salary = 6000, City = 'Cairo'
                    WHERE EmployeeID = 2;
                    
                    -- Update based on another table
                    UPDATE E
                    SET E.Salary = S.NewSalary
                    FROM Employees E
                    JOIN SalaryUpdates S ON E.EmployeeID = S.EmployeeID;

💡 Note: Always use a WHERE clause unless you intend to update ALL rows in the table.

🛠️ DML — Data Manipulation Language

DELETE

Used to remove existing records from a table.

  • Delete Specific Rows: Removing rows that match a certain condition using WHERE.
  • Delete All Rows: Removing all records from a table (use carefully).
  • Delete with JOIN: Deleting rows based on matching data in another table.

Example:

            -- Delete specific row
            DELETE FROM Employees
            WHERE EmployeeID = 5;
            
            -- Delete multiple rows by condition
            DELETE FROM Employees
            WHERE Salary < 3000;
            
            -- Delete all rows (table stays)
            DELETE FROM Employees;
            
            -- Delete using JOIN
            DELETE E
            FROM Employees E
            JOIN TerminatedList T
            ON E.EmployeeID = T.EmployeeID;

💡 Note: Always use a WHERE clause unless you intend to delete ALL rows from the table.

🛠️ DML — Data Manipulation Language

MERGE

Combines INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE operations in a single statement by comparing a target table with a source table.

  • Insert When Not Matched: Adds new rows that don't exist in the target table.
  • Update When Matched: Updates rows that exist in both tables.
  • Delete When Matched: Removes rows based on specific conditions.

Example:

            MERGE INTO Employees AS Target
            USING UpdatedEmployees AS Source
            ON Target.EmployeeID = Source.EmployeeID
            
            -- Update existing rows
            WHEN MATCHED THEN
            UPDATE SET 
            Target.Salary = Source.Salary,
            Target.City = Source.City
            
            -- Insert new rows
            WHEN NOT MATCHED BY TARGET THEN
            INSERT (EmployeeID, Name, Salary, City)
            VALUES (Source.EmployeeID, Source.Name, Source.Salary, Source.City)
            
            -- Delete rows not in source (optional)
            WHEN NOT MATCHED BY SOURCE THEN
            DELETE;
            -- Always end a MERGE with a semicolon
            ;

💡 Note: MERGE is powerful but should be used carefully. Always test with OUTPUT clause before running it on real data.

Understanding Relationship Rules

Relationships define how tables are connected and how data integrity is maintained between them.

  • Purpose: Enforce logical links between entities (tables).
  • Key Concept: Relationships are implemented using foreign keys.
  • Types: One-to-One, One-to-Many, Many-to-Many.

💡 Goal: Ensure data consistency — every child record must reference a valid parent record when required.

Referential Integrity Rules

Referential integrity ensures that relationships between tables remain valid over time.

  • Foreign Key Constraint: Prevents invalid references to non-existent parent rows.
  • ON DELETE / ON UPDATE: Defines what happens when parent data changes.
  • Actions: CASCADE, SET NULL, SET DEFAULT,NO ACTION.

Example:

                    ON DELETE CASCADE → Deletes child rows when parent is deleted.

                    ON DELETE SET NULL → Keeps child row but clears reference.

                    ON DELETE NO ACTION → Prevents deletion if child exists.

💡 Choose the right rule based on data ownership and business logic. Avoid CASCADE if deletions should be controlled manually.

Data Query Language (DQL)

DQL is used to retrieve data from databases. It focuses on querying and viewing information rather than modifying it.

  • Main Command: SELECT
  • Purpose: To fetch data from one or more tables or views.
  • Read-only: Does not modify data or schema.

💡 Tip: DQL commands form the foundation for reporting, analytics, and application data retrieval.

SELECT Statement Basics

The SELECT statement retrieves data from tables using specific columns or expressions.

  • Syntax: SELECT column1, column2 FROM table_name;
  • All Columns: Use * to return all columns
  • Aliases: Rename columns using AS

Example:

                    SELECT FirstName, LastName FROM Employees;

                    SELECT * FROM Departments;

                    SELECT FirstName AS 'Employee Name' FROM Employees;

SELECT Statement With Like

Wildcard Characters

  • _ Represents one, single character
  • % Represents zero, one, or multiple characters
  • [] Matches any single character within the specified range
  • [^] Matches any single character that is not within the range

Example:

                    _M%  => Amr , Emad 

                    [sa]%  => Ahmed , Shaimaa 

                    sa%  => Samy , Sama 

                    [^sa]%  => Mohamed , Marwa 

                    [a-m]%  => Malak , Bola  

                    [^a-m]% => Omar , Rawan

💡 Documentation Link: Wildcard Characters

Filtering and Sorting Data

DQL provides clauses to filter and order result sets for precise data retrieval.

  • WHERE: Filter rows based on conditions.
  • ORDER BY: Sort result by one or more columns.
  • TOP: Limit number of returned rows.

Example:

                    SELECT TOP 5 * FROM Employees

                    WHERE Department = 'HR'

                    ORDER BY HireDate DESC;

Aggregation and Grouping

DQL allows summarizing data using aggregate functions and grouping related rows.

  • Functions: COUNT(), SUM(), AVG(), MIN(), MAX()
  • GROUP BY: Groups rows that share a value in one or more columns.
  • HAVING: Filters aggregated results.

Example:

                    SELECT Department, COUNT(*) AS TotalEmployees

                    FROM Employees

                    GROUP BY Department

                    HAVING COUNT(*) > 5;

Joining Tables in DQL

Joins combine data from multiple tables based on relationships.

Joining Tables in DQL

  • INNER JOIN: Returns only rows with matching values in both tables.
  • LEFT JOIN: Returns all rows from the left table, plus matching rows from the right.
  • RIGHT JOIN: Returns all rows from the right table, plus matching rows from the left.
  • FULL OUTER JOIN: Returns all rows when there is a match in either table (includes non-matching rows on both sides).
  • CROSS JOIN: Returns the Cartesian product — every row from table A combined with every row from table B.
  • SELF JOIN: A table joined with itself (useful for hierarchical or related records).

Example:

                    SELECT e.Name, d.DepartmentName

                    FROM Employees e

                    INNER JOIN Departments d ON e.DeptId = d.Id;

💡 Tip: Joins are the key to relational queries — they connect normalized tables into meaningful datasets.

CROSS JOIN

Produces the cartesian product — every row from table A combined with every row from table B.

  • No ON condition required.
  • Rows = A_count × B_count.
  • Used for combinations, calendars, permutations.

💡 Tip: Use a CROSS JOIN when you need every possible combination of rows between two tables — perfect for generating test data, combinations, or pairing scenarios.

INNER JOIN

Returns rows that have matching values in both tables.

  • Most common join type.
  • Filters out non-matching rows.

💡 Note: The INNER JOIN keyword returns only rows with a match in both tables. Which means that if you have a Employee with no Dept_Id , that record would not be returned in the result

💡 Tip: Use INNER JOIN when only matched data is needed.

LEFT OUTER JOIN

Returns all rows from the left table, plus matching rows from the right.

  • Non-matching right rows appear as NULL.
  • Used when the left table is the “main” dataset.

💡 Note: The LEFT JOIN keyword returns all records from the left table (Employees), even if there are no matches in the right table (Departments)

💡 Tip: Use LEFT JOIN to keep all employees, even if they have no department.

RIGHT OUTER JOIN

Returns all rows from the right table and matching rows from the left.

  • Non-matching left rows appear as NULL.
  • Less commonly used than LEFT JOIN.

💡 Note: The Right JOIN keyword returns all records from the right table (Departments), even if there are no matches in the left table (Employees)

💡 Tip: Same as LEFT JOIN but reversed order of importance.

Returns all departments, even if they have no employees

FULL OUTER JOIN

Returns all rows when there is a match in either table.

  • Combines LEFT JOIN + RIGHT JOIN.
  • Non-matching rows on either side become NULL.

💡 Note: The FULL OUTER JOIN keyword returns all matching records from both tables whether the other table matches or not. So, if there are rows in "Employees" that do not have matches in "Departments", or if there are rows in "Departments" that do not have matches in "Employees", those rows will be listed as well.

💡 Tip: Useful for comparing differences between two datasets.

SELF JOIN

A table joined with itself to show hierarchical or relational connections.

  • Requires table aliases.
  • Common for hierarchy or parent-child relationships.

💡 Note: The self join Keyword is a regular join, but the table is joined with itself.

💡 Tip: Useful for organizational charts, reporting structures, recursive relationships.

Joining More Than Two Tables

JOINs can be chained to connect multiple related tables in one query.

  • Processed from left to right in the FROM clause.
  • Each JOIN adds another dataset to the pipeline.
  • Aliasing is strongly recommended for clarity.

💡 Note: When joining multiple tables the output of each join logically forms a virtual table that goes into the next join.

💡 Tip: Multi-table joins are essential for normalized relational databases.
